s and victims who had to contend most with maritime violence. Pirates churned up a sea of paper in their wake: letters, petitions, court documents, legal opinions, ambassadorial reports, travel accounts, captivity narratives, and vast numbers of decrees attest to their impact on lives and livelihoods. Joshua M. White plumbs the depths of these uncharted, frequently uncatalogued waters, revealing how piracy shaped both the Ottoman legal space and the contours of the Mediterranean world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aPiracy (International law)xHistoryxMediterranean Region. 0aPiracy (International law)zMediterranean RegionxHistory. 0aPiracyxHistoryxMediterranean Region. 0aPiracyxHistoryxTurkey. 0aPiracyxLaw and legislationxHistoryxMediterranean Region. 0aPiracyxLaw and legislationxHistoryxTurkey. 0aPiracyxLaw and legislationzMediterranean RegionxHistory. 0aPiracyxLaw and legislationzTurkeyxHistory. 0aPiracyzMediterranean RegionxHistory. 0aPiracyzTurkeyxHistory. 4aMediterranean. 4aOttoman Empire. 4acorsairing. 4adiplomacy. 4aearly modern. 4ainternational law. 4alaw. 4apiracy. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503603929zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503603929423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503603929.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles